Start Analysis

For this analysis, I will use linear mixed effects modeling to explore the data.

I plot each individuals BMI and age as I expect there to be significant individual difference in the changes of BMI over time.

p <- ggplot(hrs_analysis)
p <- p + geom_point(aes
                    (x=age,y=bmi
                    ))
p <- p + labs(title="Relationship of BMI and Age for Individuals")
p <- p + theme1
p <- p + facet_wrap(~id)
p

A cursory examination indicates that there is a great deal of variation between people.

Modeling

Fixed Effect Only Model (M00)

We begin by modeling a fixed-effect only model. Note that for this model and all subsequent models, indicators of model fit are calculated for later use (AIC, BIC, and deviance).

m00 <- lm(bmi~age, data=hrs_analysis)
AIC00 <- AIC(m00)
BIC00 <- BIC(m00)
dev00 <- deviance(m00)
(m00_sum <- summary(m00))

Model 0 (Empty)

We now create a model that contains the random intercept of BMI. The corresponding estimate indicates the mean BMI (~26) and its SE (~4.2). This model would be considered an empty model.

# empty model. Only intercept is modeled as random
m0 <- lme4::lmer(formula = bmi ~ 1 + (1|id), data=hrs_analysis)
AIC0 <- AIC(m0)
BIC0 <- BIC(m0)
dev0 <- deviance(m0)

Finally we graph all the models onto the data to see how well they fit. We see that there are 3 models that fit the data quite well: Models 2, 3, and 4. Due to graph size constraints, we are unable to ascertain just by looking which model is the best fit. Thus we must calculate the model that best fits the data.

pg <- ggplot2::ggplot(dsPred, aes(x=age, y=bmi)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_line(aes(y=predicted_bmi, group=model, color=model))+
  facet_wrap(~id)+
  scale_color_manual(values=c("m0"="black", "m1"="#ff7f00", "m2"="#e41a1c", "m3"="#4daf4a",
                              "m4"="#377eb8"))+
  theme1 
pg <- pg + labs(title="Relationship of BMI and Age for Individuals")
pg

Checking the Model Fits

We first combine the AIC, BIC, and deviance values for each model into 3 variables. We set these new variables into a new dataset. We use Model as the indicator for grouping.

AIC <- c(AIC00, AIC0, AIC1, AIC2, AIC3, AIC4)
BIC <- c(BIC00, BIC0, BIC1, BIC2, BIC3, BIC4)
Devall <- c(dev00, dev0, dev1, dev2, dev3, dev4)

Note that for the indices of fit, the lower the number, the better the fit. There is a small caveat when looking at deviance. Deviance will always go down when you add more variables into the model. This is a statistical artifact and does not always tell use the most efficient use of predictors that we might fit in a model.

Now we can see which model fits the data the best: Model 2

d <- data.frame(Model=0:5, AIC=0:5, BIC=0:5, dev=0:5)
d$AIC <- AIC
d$BIC <- BIC
d$dev <- Devall
d$Model <- factor(d$Model)
d$Model <- as.character(d$Model)
d$Model[d$Model == "0"] <- "Fixed Only"
d$Model[d$Model == "1"] <- "M0"
d$Model[d$Model == "2"] <- "M1"
d$Model[d$Model == "3"] <- "M2"
d$Model[d$Model == "4"] <- "M3"
d$Model[d$Model == "5"] <- "M4"
d <- melt(d, Model="Model", AIC="AIC", BIC="BIC", dev="dev")


f <- ggplot2::ggplot(d, aes(x=Model, y=value, 
                            group = variable, colour = variable)) +
  geom_point(size=4, shape=21, fill="white") +
  geom_line(aes(y=value, group=variable, color=variable))+
  theme1
f <- f + labs(title="Fit Indices for All Models")
f

Therefore, when predicting BMI in this group, using a model that contains a fixed-effect of age, random-effects of individual age slopes/intercepts, and a random intercept is the best option.
